Where it all started for me. Where I "spotted" my very 1st CLS installation, about 5 years ago. After a while, a long while living undisturbed, the piece that was installed in this very location was destroyed, bit-by-painful-bit- kinda like watching a Daddy-Long-Legs Spiders legs being pulled off. (ouch!) How this one was installed, on site- with NO ONE's "noticing" is a mystery to me...... Many of CLS's other pieces have been composed "off-site" and then,installed as an entire already manufactured item. Yet, this one,and the one on Milwaukee Avenue near the Logan Blue Line Station @ Kedzie Avenue appear to be assembled, piece by piece- on site. So let me see...someone pulls up, (on a bike I'm guessing- part of my profile I've developed) with a stack of sticks in a bag - whips out their cordless power drill/driver (probably a Makita or possibly a Rigid brand- again profiling) and starts out arranging their pieces on the ground, deciding which stick(s) to install where, and no one sees/says/questions the process of Street Art/ Urban Glorification.... I jus' don't see it??! Check out my "set" of other Public Art pieces around Chicago's byways.... flic.kr/s/aHsjqjrenx

photo.title: Millennium Park in a new light

description._content: If you are viewing it, please says something about it, give a critique, leave a comment, and/or favorite it, it's good karma, common courtesy and much appreciated! ZL-Photography
Partially buffed : /

Cloud Gate, the commandingly large sculpture by artist Anish Kapoor known affectionately as "The Bean" is the focus of a new project that will make you smile. Built on the site of Chicago's Millenium Park, Kapoor's sculpture has remained a popular attraction since its christening in 2006, though one duo is finding new potential for Cloud Gate. The two-person collective of Petra Bachmaier and Sean Gallero, aka Luftwerk, devised a vision that uses the reflexive properties of Kapoor's enormous sculpture to create a mesmerizing light show. For Luminous Field, the duo set up a series of projectors that bounce the choreographed light sequences off of Cloud Gate to create a type of futuristic dance floor. The orchestrated lights are set to music by Owen Clayton Condon of Third Coast Percussion, creating an experience that is wildly expressive while still calculated. Luminous Field will mark the first site-specific work since Cloud Gate's construction in 2004. Luminous Field will run until February 20th If you are viewing it, please says something about it, give a critique, leave a comment, and/or favorite it, it's good karma, common courtesy and much appreciated!
